(* ### Problem
 The circle graph shows the favorite ice cream flavors of those surveyed. What fraction of people surveyed selected either chocolate or strawberry as their favorite flavor of ice cream? [asy]
size(200);
draw(Circle((0,0),10));
draw((0,10)--(0,-10));
draw((0,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,0)--(10*cos(pi/5),10*sin(pi/5)));
label("50\%",(-5,0),N);
label("Chocolate",(-5,0),S);
label("25\%",(4,-5),N);
label("Vanilla",(4,-5),S);
label("15\%",(2,6),N);
label("Mint",(2,6),S);
label("10\%",(8,2),N);
label("Strawberry",(7,2),S);
[/asy] The final Answer is \frac{3}{5}
 ### Proof
 Since $50\%$ selected chocolate and $10\%$ selected strawberry as their favorite flavor, then overall $50\%+10\%=60\%$ chose chocolate or strawberry as their favorite flavor.
 Now $$60\% = \frac{60}{100}=\frac{3}{5},$$so $\boxed{\frac{3}{5}}$ of the people surveyed selected chocolate or strawberry as their favorite flavor.
 *)

theorem
fixes chocolate vanilla mint strawberry :: real
assumes h0 : "chocolate + vanilla + mint + strawberry = 1"
and h1 : "chocolate = 0.5"
and h2 : "vanilla = 0.25"
and h3 : "mint = 0.15"
and h4 : "strawberry = 0.1"
shows  "chocolate + strawberry = 0.6"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

